Men and their hypocrisy.

In The Great Indian Kitchen
the harsh reality of patriarchy is laid bare. Every time the camera shifts to a female character
she is seen in the kitchen
tirelessly preparing food while the men in the house remain detached from the effort. These men are shown lounging around
scrolling through videos on their phones
completely immersed in their own worlds

seemingly unaware or indifferent to the work being done around them.

The most glaring hypocrisy
is how they eat. When they sit at the dining table
they consume their food without a second thought for the mess they leave behind. Crumbs and food waste are scattered all over the table
yet the men have no intention of cleaning up. They walk away
leaving the women to do the dirty work. The camera lingers on the aftermath
capturing the unspoken expectation that women will bear the burden of cleaning up

without so much as a thank you.

But the hypocrisy doesnât end there. When these same men step outside the house
they suddenly transform. At restaurants or in public spaces
and make sure they donât leave a trace of their meal behind. They conform to social norms
maintaining cleanliness and etiquette when others are watching. Yet
within the confines of their own home
where women bear the brunt of domestic labor
the standard drops. They indulge in their privilege

showing no respect for the women who clean up after them.

The film captures these moments beautifully
especially the scenes in the kitchen. The camera zooms in on the food being prepared
making you imagine just how delicious it must taste. But as the focus shifts to the women
who are working tirelessly to create these meals

the beauty of the shots becomes haunting. Their faces tell the story of invisible labor.

Mutton Pickle | non veg Pickle |Soul Of Sumi
The non -veg pickle is totally mouth-watering and Indians love pickles  the most and so do . The dish does not require too many ingredients and is a spicy dish and spicy flavor can be adjusted according to our needs pairs up amazingly well with curd rice and plain rice too Mutton pickle simply tastes amazing and irresistible.

Ingredients 
Mutton 1/2 kg (bone less ) 
Ginger garlic paste 1 tbsp 
Turmeric powder  1 tsp 

Pickle masala powder 
Mustard seeds 2 tbsp 
Fenugreek seeds 2 tablespoons 
Cumin seeds 2 tablespoons 

Tempering 
Seasame oil 
Curry leaves 
Dry chilli 
Juice of 2 lemons 
Mustard seeds 
Red chilli powder 1 tbsp
